Experiment 2: Custom CNN on 193 Images

The dataset was expanded from 159 images to 193 images by adding newly collected and manually labeled capacitor images.

Result:

Test Accuracy: 47.62%

Confusion Matrix:

[[2 3 0 1]
[1 4 0 0]
[1 2 0 1]
[0 2 0 4]]

Observation:

Performance dropped significantly after increasing dataset diversity. The model struggled to classify several classes correctly, particularly the Right orientation. Multiple misclassifications were observed, and the model continued to exhibit weak orientation sensitivity.

Conclusion:

The simple CNN architecture was unable to generalize effectively on the larger and more diverse dataset.

Experiment 3: MobileNetV2 (Frozen)

A pretrained MobileNetV2 model using ImageNet weights was trained on the same 193-image dataset. The MobileNetV2 feature extraction layers were kept frozen.

Result:

Test Accuracy: 76.19%

Confusion Matrix:

[[5 0 0 1]
[0 5 0 0]
[0 1 3 0]
[0 1 2 3]]

Classification Summary:

Bottom F1 Score: 0.91
Left F1 Score: 0.83
Right F1 Score: 0.67
Top F1 Score: 0.60

Observation:

The MobileNetV2 model produced a large improvement over the custom CNN. It successfully learned all four classes, including the Right class that the CNN struggled with. The model also generated more meaningful confidence scores when tested on unseen capacitor images.

Conclusion:

Transfer learning significantly improved classification performance and generalization.

Experiment 4: Rotation Testing

Several unseen capacitor images were rotated by 0°, 90°, 180°, and 270° and evaluated using MobileNetV2.

Observation:

The model frequently changed predictions when the image was rotated by 90° or 270°, indicating that it had learned orientation-related features. However, images rotated by 180° were often classified similarly to the original image. This behavior is likely caused by the partial symmetry of capacitor top markings and polarity indicators.

Conclusion:

MobileNetV2 demonstrated substantially better orientation awareness than the custom CNN, although perfect rotational understanding was not achieved.

Experiment 5: MobileNetV2 Fine-Tuning

The upper layers of MobileNetV2 were unfrozen and fine-tuned using a small learning rate.

Result:

Test Accuracy: 76.19%

Confusion Matrix:

[[5 0 0 1]
[0 5 0 0]
[0 1 3 0]
[0 1 2 3]]

Observation:

Fine-tuning did not improve accuracy or class-wise performance. The results remained identical to the frozen MobileNetV2 model.

Conclusion:

The dataset size and diversity appear to be the primary limiting factors rather than the model architecture.

Overall Findings
Transfer learning using MobileNetV2 significantly outperformed the custom CNN architecture.
Increasing dataset size alone did not guarantee better performance.
MobileNetV2 achieved the best balance between accuracy and generalization.
Rotation testing showed that MobileNetV2 learned orientation-related features more effectively than the CNN.
Further improvement is likely to come from collecting more diverse capacitor images rather than increasing model complexity.
Best Performing Model

Model: MobileNetV2 (Frozen)

Test Accuracy: 76.19%

This model is currently used as the final model for inference and evaluation.
